The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro
 Thursday, April 15, 2004  The City Diary
																																																																																		The state governments plans to conduct counselling for post-graduate medical seats on Thursday suffered a setback after the Supreme Court ordered a stay on the matter. On Tuesday evening, the government received a communique from the director of medical education of the central government, Anup Pandey, asking them not to hold the counselling. A furore recently broke out after the Centre mooted the idea of raising the all-India reservations for post-graduate medical seats from 25 to 50 per cent. A public interest litigation was filed in the Supreme Court by a group of students and the case is underway. The Supreme Court, earlier this week, observed that unless the original case was disposed off, counselling could not be held in the medical colleges of the city. 																																																		Large parts of central Calcutta were plunged into darkness after a major fault developed in the 132KV circuit of the CESC from Titagarh to Prinsep Street on Wednesday evening. As a result, three out of four transformers tripped at the private power utilitys distribution centre on Prinsep Street at around 7.10 pm, leading to power failure in large parts of central Calcutta. Engineers swung into action and by 8.30 pm, were able to restore power in most of the affected areas. A CESC spokesperson said repair work would be completed by Wednesday night.																																																		Five persons were seriously injured on Wednesday evening on BT Road in the Cossipore police station area when two Shyambazar-bound buses on the same route trying to overtake one another collided head-on with another bus coming from the opposite direction. According to police sources, the injured passengers were taken to RG Kar Hospital where they are undergoing treatment. The three drivers were arrested and the vehicles were impounded.																																																		Two criminals, Mazed Mandal, 23, and Hasanujjaman, 24, were lynched on Tuesday night in Barasat on the northern fringes of the city after they shot at a local youth, Enayat. According to police, the two were associates of Saiful, who has three cases of murder pending against him. Investigations revealed that the two had come to kill Enayat as he was in Saifuls way. Five persons were detained for questioning.																																																		A 45-year-old man, Chitta Majumdar, hanged himself from the ceiling of his bedroom on Wednesday morning at Sripalli in Barasat, on the northern fringes of the city. According to police, Majumdar was suffering from depression ever since he lost his son, a Class VII student who had also committed suicide following a difference of opinion with his parents over a petty issue. His wife was admitted in a local hospital after she fell ill at the news of her husbands death. To residents of Anandapur, in Thakurpukur, for forming a resistance group to deal with frequent political clashes in the area
